{"title_page": "OCP Group", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = OCP Group\n| logo = Ocp.jpg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| founded = 1920\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Casablanca]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Morocco]]\n| key_people = [[Mostafa Terrab]] (Chairman)\n| industry = Phosphates, Chemicals\n| revenue = {{increase}} US$5.884 &nbsp;billion\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = \n| net_income = {{increase}} US$586.42&nbsp;million\n| net_income_year = 2018\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (when known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (when known) -->\n| owner = [[Politics of Morocco|Government of Morocco]] (95%)\n| num_employees = about 20.000\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (when known) -->\n| subsid = '''Mining & processing'''<br/><br/>Phosboucra\u00e2<br/>Prayon<br/>Euro Maroc Phosphore<br/>Jorf Fertilizer Company<br/>Indo Maroc Phosphore<br/>Pakistan Maroc Phosphore<br/>Zuari Maroc Phosphates Limited<br/>Paradeep Phosphates Limited<br/><br/>'''International & trading'''<br/><br/>OCP International<br/>OCP Fertilizantes<br/>OCP de Argentina<br/>OCP do Brazil<br/>Black Sea Fertilizer Trading Company<br/>OCP Africa<br/><br/>'''Engineering & Consulting'''<br/><br/>[[Jacobs Engineering S.A]]<br/>OCP Solutions<br/><br/>Teal Technology Services<br/><br/>Transportation Engineering and Management Consultants<br/>DuPont OCP Operations Consulting<br/><br/>'''Ecosystem Development'''<br/><br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement Vert<br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement de Mazagan<br/>OCP Innovation Fund for Agriculture<br/>Fondation OCP<br/>Fondation Phosboucra\u00e2\n| footnotes = \n| website = http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en\n}}\n\nThe '''OCP Group''' (OCP S.A.) (formerly Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates) is a Moroccan based phosphate rock miner, phosphoric acid manufacturer and phosphate fertilizer producer. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates (Morocco)|url=http://www.solpart-project.eu/about-us/partners/ocp/ |journal=Solpart Project|date = 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group: Major Business Opportunities|url=http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|journal=SYITC|date = November 1, 2016}}</ref> Founded in 1920, the company has grown into one of the world\u2019s largest producers of phosphate and phosphate-based products.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Company Overview of OCP S.A.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=5476844|journal=Bloomberg|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group Client|url=http://www.architectepartners.com/ocp-group-client-6-Part-191.html|journal=Architecte Partners|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Maroc |url=https://www.blacktogreen.com/portfolio_item/ocp-maroc/|journal=Black to Green|date = 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-05/RA%20OCP%202017%20VUK.pdf|title=2017 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOCP has access to more than 70% of the world\u2019s phosphate rock reserves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nmic/phosphate-rock-statistics-and-information|title=Phosphate Rock Statistics and Information|website=www.usgs.gov|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Initially a mining company, OCP has diversified in 1965 to become a phosphate processor, making it one of the world\u2019s leading fertilizer manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en|title=Home {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The company holds a 31% market share of the world phosphate product market.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe group employs nearly 23,000 people in Morocco and a number of international subsidiaries. In 2018, its revenues amounted to US$5.884 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/who-we-are/ocp-glance|title=OCP at a glance {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== '''Origins''' ===\nThe OCP Group was founded in Morocco in 1920 as the Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates following Royal Decree. \u00a0[AC1] Mining production began in 1921, when it began extracting phosphate rockat its first mine in Khouribga. Transportation of the phosphate to the port of Casablanca also started in 1921, allowing the first export of phosphate that year. Subsequently, OCP launched other mining sites in Youssoufia in 1931 and in Benguerir in 1976, and launched chemical production in Safi in 1965 and in Jorf Lasfar in 1984. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/1962/06/A/24781|title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates amorce une nouvelle phase d'expansion|date=1962-06-01|website=Le Monde diplomatique|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership ===\nIn 2008, the OCP Group became a limited company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emis.com/php/company-profile/MA/Office_Chrifien_des_Phosphates_Group__OCP___%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%AC%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%B9_%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%98%C2%B4%C3%98%C2%B1%C3%99%C2%8A%C3%99%C2%81_%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%81%C3%99%C2%88%C3%98%C2%B3%C3%99%C2%81%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%98%C2%B7__en_3853612.html|title=Office Chrifien des Phosphates Group (OCP) Company Profile - Morocco {{!}} Financials & Key Executives {{!}} EMIS|website=www.emis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Currently 95% of the OCP Group is owned by the Moroccan state and 5% by Banque Centrale Populaire investment funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html|title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|date=2012-01-17|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate Timeline ===\n\n* '''1920''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates founded\n* '''1921''' Launch of mining production in Khouribga\n* '''1931''' Launch of mining production in Youssoufia\n* '''1965''' Launch of chemical production in Safi\n* '''1976''' Acquisition of 65% of Phosboucraa \n* '''1980''' Launch of mining production at Benguerir site\n* '''1984''' Launch of chemical production at Jorf Lasfar\n* '''1996''' Construction of purified phosphoric acid plant launched in Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2002''' OCP becomes sole owner of Phosboucraa\n* '''2006''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates becomes OCP \n* '''2008''' Transformation of Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates into a Corporation (OCP S.A)\n* '''2011''' Joint Venture with Jacobs Engineering\n* '''2013''' Joint Venture with DuPont de Nemours\n* '''2014''' Launch of the Slurry Pipeline between Khouribga and Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2016''' Creation of OCP Africa\n* '''2018''' Inauguration of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University and Joint Venture with IBM\n\nIn 2007, the OCP Group set itself a target to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.\n\nThe OCP Group plays an important economic and social role in Morocco. The value of phosphates and their derivatives represented nearly a quarter of the country's exports and approximately 3.5% of the GDP in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Pr\u00e9sentation d'OCP|url=http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|journal=Site de la World Policy Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 14, 2016|title=L'OCP: Le g\u00e9ant des phosphates made in Morocco|url=http://www.agrimaroc.ma/l-ocp-l-office-cherifien-des-phosphates/|journal=Agrimaroc}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fitch Ratings confirmed the rating of \"investment grade\" for the OCP Group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-fitch-confirme-l-investment-grade-a-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89?article=46364|journal=Les Afriques}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|journal=Afropages}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=April 3, 2014|title=Fitch Rates Morocco's OCP 'BBB-'; Proposed Notes 'BBB-(EXP)'|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFFit69584420140403|journal=Reuters Africa}}</ref>\n\nAfter approval from the AMMC ((Moroccan Authority of the Capital Market) Autorit\u00e9 Marocaine du March\u00e9 des Capitaux) on December 9, 2016, the OCP Group managed to reach 10.2&nbsp;billion dirhams of bonds from the national community. This loan is the largest ever made in the Moroccan market.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 23, 2016|title=Carton plein pour l'\u00e9mission obligataire d'OCP|url=http://telquel.ma/2016/12/23/banco-lemission-obligataire-docp_1528395|journal=Telquel}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 19, 2016|title=OCP cl\u00f4ture avec succ\u00e8s son \u00e9mission obligataire|url=http://www.leconomiste.com/flash-infos/ocp-cloture-avec-succes-son-emission-obligataire|journal=L'\u00e9conomiste}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 29, 2016|title=OCP : L'AMMC donne son feu vert \u00e0 un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=https://www.yabiladi.com/articles/details/48810/l-ammc-donne-vert-emprunt-obligataire.html|journal=Yabiladi}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 14, 2014|title=OCP: \u00e9mission d'un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|journal=24h Info}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 1, 2016|title=OCP finance l'expansion de son appareil productif et apure ses dettes|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/378734/economie/ocp-finance-lexpansion-de-appareil-productif-apure-dettes/|journal=Jeune Afrique}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group in the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 12 African countries.\n\nIn the same year, OCP adopted a new internal culture, called \u2018Le Movement\u2019, aimed at re-focusing the group even more strongly on innovation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gasteyger|first=Curt|title=Chapitre VII. Les armements dans le tiers-monde|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.iheid.4492|work=Les d\u00e9fis de la paix|pages=99\u2013109|publisher=Graduate Institute Publications|isbn=978-2-13-039917-9|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== The group ==\nThe Group's activities are organised into an integrated model covering all operations of the value chain from the extraction of phosphates to the production and marketing of various products including fertilizers and phosphoric acid.<ref name=lexpress>{{cite journal |title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html |journal=Jeune Afrique|date = January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, the OCP Group aims to double its annual phosphate production capacity by 2017 (to reach a production capacity of fertilizers of almost 12 million tonnes)<ref>{{cite journal |title=Le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates se sacre roi des engrais|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2016/02/02/le-geant-marocain-des-phosphates-se-sacre-roi-des-engrais_4858243_3212.html|journal=Le Monde Afrique|date = February 2, 2016}}</ref> and to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.<ref name=lexpress/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mission au Maroc: convention entre le centre de formation li\u00e9geois Technifutur et l'OCP|url=http://www.lesoir.be/actualite/economie/2012-05-23/mission-au-maroc-convention-entre-le-centre-de-formation-liegeois-technifutur-et-l-ocp-917492.php|journal=Le soir|date = May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== OCP Africa ===\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group on the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 5 African countries. The subsidiary was granted the status of Casablanca Finance City (CFC) for investors on the African continent to benefit from an attractive package of tax incentives and other opportunities.<ref name=Agefi>{{cite journal |title=Trading \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve pour le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates|url=http://www.agefi.com/quotidien-agefi/suisse/detail/edition/2016-06-03/article/ocp-loffice-cherifien-des-phosphates-vient-douvrir-une-entite-de-negoce-en-suisse-sous-le-nom-de-saftco--428186.html|journal=Agefi|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group launches new subsidiary|url=http://www.africanfarming.net/crops/agriculture/ocp-group-launches-new-subsidiary|journal=African Farming|date = March 30, 2016}}</ref> The OCP projects in Africa cover the entire value chain, including the local construction of fertilizer plants, the development of logistics and distribution capabilities, as well as investment in research for the development of formulas adapted for the soils and crops (mapping the African soil fertility and respective fertilizer needs). The African Development Bank (ADB) has pledged to support the various initiatives of the OCP Group in favour of the African continent.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : Akinwumi Adesina chez Terrab, PDG OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-akinwumi-adesina-chez-terrab-pdg-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89|journal=Les Afriques|date = July 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Le groupe OCP lance sa filiale OCP Africa pour renforcer le d\u00e9veloppement agricole de l'Afrique |url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/02/25/ocp-africa-nouvelle-filiale-developpement-agricole_n_9318388.html |journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire/International/ Le PDG du Groupe OCP re\u00e7oit le Pr\u00e9sident du Groupe de la BAD (Communiqu\u00e9)|url=http://news.abidjan.net/h/595029.html|journal=Abidjan.net|date = July 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=A la COP 22, l'accord sur l'agriculture en friche|url=http://www.liberation.fr/planete/2016/11/17/a-la-cop-22-l-accord-sur-l-agriculture-en-friche_1529165|journal=Lib\u00e9ration|date = November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe OCP Group plans to open 14 new branches in Sub-Saharan Africa to make a promising entry into the African market. The main countries targeted by this operation are: [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Senegal]], [[the Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Benin]], [[Cameroon]], Nigeria, [[Tanzania]], [[Angola]], [[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]], [[Kenya]], [[Ghana]], and [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : le groupe OCP pr\u00e9voit 14 nouvelles filiales en Afrique subsaharienne|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/08/05/maroc-le-groupe-ocp-prevoit-14-nouvelles-filiales-en-afrique-subsaharienne/|journal=Financial Afrik|date = August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Nigeria]] ====\nIn 2016, the Morrocan head of state and King Mohammed VI presided over the ceremony marking the launch of a strategic partnership for the development of the fertilizer industry in Nigeria. In particular, this partnership includes an agreement between the OCP Group and Dangote Industries Limited for creating a platform for fertilizer production in Nigeria. Similarly, an agreement for developing the fertilizer market was signed between the OCP Group and the association of fertilizer producers and suppliers in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc/Nig\u00e9ria : Plusieurs accords sign\u00e9s aujourd'hui, les d\u00e9tails|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/marocnigeria-plusieurs-accords-signes-aujourdhui-les-details|journal=Infom\u00e9diaire|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi et le Chef de l'Etat nig\u00e9rian pr\u00e9sident la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de lancement d'un partenariat strat\u00e9gique pour le d\u00e9veloppement de l'industrie des engrais au Nig\u00e9ria|url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-et-le-chef-de-letat-nigerian-president-la-ceremonie-de-lancement-dun-partenariat-strategique-pour-le-developpement-de-lindustrie-des-engrais-au-nigeria/|journal=MA Express|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Accord OCP-Dangote: quand le premier producteur mondial d\u2019engrais tend la main \u00e0 l\u2019homme le plus riche d\u2019Afrique|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/12/03/accord-ocp-dangote-quand-le-premier-producteur-mondial-dengrais-tend-la-main-a-lhomme-le-plus-riche-dafrique/#.WIHjALbhDUI|journal=Financial Afrik|date = December 3, 2016}}</ref> Likewise, a pipeline project linking Nigeria to Morocco, passing through several countries in West Africa, is about to take shape.<ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest |url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-a-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc-reliant-le-nigeria-au-maroc-a-travers-plusieurs-pays-dafrique-de-louest-cabinet-royal/|journal=Agence de presse marocaine|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest|url=http://www.maroc.ma/fr/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc|journal=Maroc|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Alerte : Le Maroc passe \u00e0 l'acte pour le gazoduc g\u00e9ant, r\u00e9union royale \u00e0 Casablanca|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|journal=InfoM\u00e9diaire |date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Gazoduc nig\u00e9ria-maroc: le roi pr\u00e9side une s\u00e9ance de travail sur la faisabilit\u00e9 et le financement |url=http://www.bladi.info/threads/gazoduc-nigeria-maroc-roi-preside.445289/|journal=Bladi|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mohammed VI \u00e9tudie la faisabilit\u00e9 technique et le financement du projet de gazoduc|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/12/13/mohammed-vi-etudie-faisabilite-technique-financement-projet-gazoduc_n_13606152.html?ir=Maroc|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Rwanda]] ====\nIn October 2016, during the visit of King Mohammed VI, the Ministry of Agriculture and Animal Resources signed an agreement with the OCP Group for the construction of a fertilizer plant in the country to facilitate access to these local farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Rwanda's move towards green agric gains momentum|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2016-12-11/206163/|journal=The New Times|date = December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Saftco ===\nOn May 25, 2016, the OCP Group opened a commodity trading entity in Switzerland that includes phosphate, fertilizers and chemical products.<ref name=Agefi/><ref>{{cite journal |title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates ouvre une filiale \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/06/03/ocp-geneve-maroc_n_10274720.html|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Financial information ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n |+ Figures 2009 \u2013 2018\n |-\n |\n !scope=\"col\"| 2009\n !scope=\"col\"| 2010\n !scope=\"col\"| 2011\n !scope=\"col\"| 2012\n !scope=\"col\"| 2013\n !scope=\"col\"| 2014\n !scope=\"col\"| 2015\n !scope=\"col\"| 2016\n !scope=\"col\"| 2017\n !scope=\"col\"| 2018 \n |-\n !scope=\"row\"| Turnover (billions of MAD)\n | 25.3\n | 43.5\n | 56.4\n | 59.4\n |46.2\n |41.4\n |47.7\n |42.5\n |48.5\n |55.9\n|-\n ! scope=\"row\" | Profit (billions of MAD)\n | 1.3\n | 8.8\n | 16.3\n | 14.1\n |7.1\n |7.6\n |\n |\n |\n |5.4\n |\n |}\n\n== Executives (2016) ==\n\n=== Top Management ===\n* Chairman & CEO: [[Mostafa Terrab]]\n\n=== Senior Management ===\n* Executive vice president strategy & corporate development : Marouane Ameziane\n* Executive vice president sales & marketing : Mohamed Belhoussain\n* Executive vice president legal & corporate affairs : Otmane Bennani-Smires\n* Executive vice president human capital: Faris Derrij\n* Executive vice president industrial development: Abdelaziz El Mallah\n* Executive vice president industrial operations: Iliass Elfali\n* Executive vice president performance Management : Nada Elmajdoub\n* Executive vice president chief financial officer: Ghislane Guedira\n* Executive vice president digital office : Mohamed Laklalech\n* Executive vice president Africa : Karim Lotfi Senhadji\n\n== 2020 coronavirus crisis response ==\nOCP Group contributed $310 million the Moroccan emergency fund, created by [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|King Mohammed IV]] on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/296549/moroccan-government-members-donate-salaries-to-covid-19-fund/|title=Moroccan Government Members Donate Salaries to COVID-19 Fund|last=Hekking|first=Morgan|date=2020-03-17|website=Morocco World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-morocco-idUSKBN212173|title=Morocco to create $1 billion fund to counter coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en Official website of the OCP Group]\n* [http://www.ocpafrica.com/ Official website of OCP Africa]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economy of Morocco]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Office Cherifien des Phosphates}}\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Phosphate mining]]\n[[Category:Fertilizer companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Mining companies of Morocco]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = OCP Group\n| logo = Ocp.jpg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| founded = 1920\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Casablanca]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Morocco]]\n| key_people = [[Mostafa Terrab]] (Chairman)\n| industry = Phosphates, Chemicals\n| revenue = {{increase}} US$5.884 &nbsp;billion\n| revenue_year = 2018\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = \n| net_income = {{increase}} US$586.42&nbsp;million\n| net_income_year = 2018\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (when known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (when known) -->\n| owner = [[Politics of Morocco|Government of Morocco]] (95%)\n| num_employees = about 20.000\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (when known) -->\n| subsid = '''Mining & processing'''<br/><br/>Phosboucra\u00e2<br/>Prayon<br/>Euro Maroc Phosphore<br/>Jorf Fertilizer Company<br/>Indo Maroc Phosphore<br/>Pakistan Maroc Phosphore<br/>Zuari Maroc Phosphates Limited<br/>Paradeep Phosphates Limited<br/><br/>'''International & trading'''<br/><br/>OCP International<br/>OCP Fertilizantes<br/>OCP de Argentina<br/>OCP do Brazil<br/>Black Sea Fertilizer Trading Company<br/>OCP Africa<br/><br/>'''Engineering & Consulting'''<br/><br/>[[Jacobs Engineering S.A]]<br/>OCP Solutions<br/><br/>Teal Technology Services<br/><br/>Transportation Engineering and Management Consultants<br/>DuPont OCP Operations Consulting<br/><br/>'''Ecosystem Development'''<br/><br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement Vert<br/>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Am\u00e9nagement et de D\u00e9veloppement de Mazagan<br/>OCP Innovation Fund for Agriculture<br/>Fondation OCP<br/>Fondation Phosboucra\u00e2\n| footnotes = \n| website = http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en\n}}\n\nThe '''OCP Group''' (OCP S.A.) (formerly Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates) is a Moroccan based phosphate rock miner, phosphoric acid manufacturer and phosphate fertilizer producer. <ref>{{cite journal |title=Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates (Morocco)|url=http://www.solpart-project.eu/about-us/partners/ocp/ |journal=Solpart Project|date = 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group: Major Business Opportunities|url=http://www.syitc.com/events/ocp-group-major-business-opportunities/|journal=SYITC|date = November 1, 2016}}</ref> Founded in 1920, the company has grown into one of the world\u2019s largest producers of phosphate and phosphate-based products.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Company Overview of OCP S.A.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=5476844|journal=Bloomberg|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group Client|url=http://www.architectepartners.com/ocp-group-client-6-Part-191.html|journal=Architecte Partners|date = 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Maroc |url=https://www.blacktogreen.com/portfolio_item/ocp-maroc/|journal=Black to Green|date = 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/sites/default/files/2019-05/RA%20OCP%202017%20VUK.pdf|title=2017 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOCP has access to more than 70% of the world\u2019s phosphate rock reserves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nmic/phosphate-rock-statistics-and-information|title=Phosphate Rock Statistics and Information|website=www.usgs.gov|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Initially a mining company, OCP has diversified in 1965 to become a phosphate processor, making it one of the world\u2019s leading fertilizer manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en|title=Home {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> The company holds a 31% market share of the world phosphate product market.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe group employs nearly 23,000 people in Morocco and a number of international subsidiaries. In 2018, its revenues amounted to US$5.884 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocpgroup.ma/en/who-we-are/ocp-glance|title=OCP at a glance {{!}} OCP GROUP|website=www.ocpgroup.ma|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== '''Origins''' ===\nThe OCP Group was founded in Morocco in 1920 as the Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates following Royal Decree. \u00a0[AC1] Mining production began in 1921, when it began extracting phosphate rockat its first mine in Khouribga. Transportation of the phosphate to the port of Casablanca also started in 1921, allowing the first export of phosphate that year. Subsequently, OCP launched other mining sites in Youssoufia in 1931 and in Benguerir in 1976, and launched chemical production in Safi in 1965 and in Jorf Lasfar in 1984. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/1962/06/A/24781|title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates amorce une nouvelle phase d'expansion|date=1962-06-01|website=Le Monde diplomatique|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership ===\nIn 2008, the OCP Group became a limited company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emis.com/php/company-profile/MA/Office_Chrifien_des_Phosphates_Group__OCP___%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%AC%C3%99%C2%85%C3%98%C2%B9_%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%99%C2%84%C3%98%C2%B4%C3%98%C2%B1%C3%99%C2%8A%C3%99%C2%81_%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%84%C3%99%C2%81%C3%99%C2%88%C3%98%C2%B3%C3%99%C2%81%C3%98%C2%A7%C3%98%C2%B7__en_3853612.html|title=Office Chrifien des Phosphates Group (OCP) Company Profile - Morocco {{!}} Financials & Key Executives {{!}} EMIS|website=www.emis.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Currently 95% of the OCP Group is owned by the Moroccan state and 5% by Banque Centrale Populaire investment funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html|title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|date=2012-01-17|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.le360.ma/economie/ocp-group-reduit-sa-participation-dans-la-bcp-29317|title=OCP Group r\u00e9duit sa participation dans la BCP|website=fr.le360.ma|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate Timeline ===\n\n* '''1920''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates founded\n* '''1921'''Launch of mining production in Khouribga\n* '''1931''' Launch of mining production in Youssoufia\n* '''1965''' Launch of chemical production in Safi\n* '''1976''' Acquisition of 65% of Phosboucraa \n* '''1980''' Launch of mining production at Benguerir site\n* '''1984''' Launch of chemical production at Jorf Lasfar\n* '''1996''' Construction of purified phosphoric acid plant launched in Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2002''' OCP becomes sole owner of Phosboucraa\n* '''2006''' Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates becomes OCP \n* '''2008''' Transformation of Office Ch\u00e9rifien des Phosphates into a Corporation (OCP S.A)\n* '''2011''' Joint Venture with Jacobs Engineering\n* '''2013''' Joint Venture with DuPont de Nemours\n* '''2014''' Launch of the Slurry Pipeline between Khouribga and Jorf Lasfar\n* '''2016''' Creation of OCP Africa\n* '''2018''' Inauguration of Mohammed VI Polytechnic University and Joint Venture with IBM\n\nIn 2007, the OCP Group set itself a target to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.\n\nThe OCP Group plays an important economic and social role in Morocco. The value of phosphates and their derivatives represented nearly a quarter of the country's exports and approximately 3.5% of the GDP in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2010|title=Pr\u00e9sentation d'OCP|url=http://www.worldpolicyconference.com/presse.php?lien=sponsorpresse&&menu=2&&lang=fr&&edition=2010|journal=Site de la World Policy Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 14, 2016|title=L'OCP: Le g\u00e9ant des phosphates made in Morocco|url=http://www.agrimaroc.ma/l-ocp-l-office-cherifien-des-phosphates/|journal=Agrimaroc}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fitch Ratings confirmed the rating of \"investment grade\" for the OCP Group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-fitch-confirme-l-investment-grade-a-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89?article=46364|journal=Les Afriques}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 15, 2016|title=Maroc : Fitch confirme l'Investment Grade \u00e0 OCP Group|url=https://www.afropages.fr/Les-Afriques/maroc-fitch-confirme-linvestment-grade-a-ocp-group|journal=Afropages}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=April 3, 2014|title=Fitch Rates Morocco's OCP 'BBB-'; Proposed Notes 'BBB-(EXP)'|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFFit69584420140403|journal=Reuters Africa}}</ref>\n\nAfter approval from the AMMC ((Moroccan Authority of the Capital Market) Autorit\u00e9 Marocaine du March\u00e9 des Capitaux) on December 9, 2016, the OCP Group managed to reach 10.2&nbsp;billion dirhams of bonds from the national community. This loan is the largest ever made in the Moroccan market.<ref>{{cite journal|date=December 23, 2016|title=Carton plein pour l'\u00e9mission obligataire d'OCP|url=http://telquel.ma/2016/12/23/banco-lemission-obligataire-docp_1528395|journal=Telquel}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 19, 2016|title=OCP cl\u00f4ture avec succ\u00e8s son \u00e9mission obligataire|url=http://www.leconomiste.com/flash-infos/ocp-cloture-avec-succes-son-emission-obligataire|journal=L'\u00e9conomiste}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=November 29, 2016|title=OCP : L'AMMC donne son feu vert \u00e0 un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=https://www.yabiladi.com/articles/details/48810/l-ammc-donne-vert-emprunt-obligataire.html|journal=Yabiladi}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 14, 2014|title=OCP: \u00e9mission d'un emprunt obligataire de 5 milliards de dirhams|url=http://www.h24info.ma/economie/entreprises/ocp-emission-dun-emprunt-obligataire-de-5-milliards-de-dirhams/49090|journal=24h Info}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=December 1, 2016|title=OCP finance l'expansion de son appareil productif et apure ses dettes|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/378734/economie/ocp-finance-lexpansion-de-appareil-productif-apure-dettes/|journal=Jeune Afrique}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group in the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 12 African countries.\n\nIn the same year, OCP adopted a new internal culture, called \u2018Le Movement\u2019, aimed at re-focusing the group even more strongly on innovation.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gasteyger|first=Curt|title=Chapitre VII. Les armements dans le tiers-monde|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.iheid.4492|work=Les d\u00e9fis de la paix|pages=99\u2013109|publisher=Graduate Institute Publications|isbn=978-2-13-039917-9|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== The group ==\nThe Group's activities are organised into an integrated model covering all operations of the value chain from the extraction of phosphates to the production and marketing of various products including fertilizers and phosphoric acid.<ref name=lexpress>{{cite journal |title=Maroc: le nouvel \u00e2ge d'or des phosphates|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/monde/afrique/maroc-le-nouvel-age-d-or-des-phosphates_1072371.html |journal=Jeune Afrique|date = January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, the OCP Group aims to double its annual phosphate production capacity by 2017 (to reach a production capacity of fertilizers of almost 12 million tonnes)<ref>{{cite journal |title=Le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates se sacre roi des engrais|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/afrique/article/2016/02/02/le-geant-marocain-des-phosphates-se-sacre-roi-des-engrais_4858243_3212.html|journal=Le Monde Afrique|date = February 2, 2016}}</ref> and to triple its production of fertilizers by 2020.<ref name=lexpress/><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mission au Maroc: convention entre le centre de formation li\u00e9geois Technifutur et l'OCP|url=http://www.lesoir.be/actualite/economie/2012-05-23/mission-au-maroc-convention-entre-le-centre-de-formation-liegeois-technifutur-et-l-ocp-917492.php|journal=Le soir|date = May 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== OCP Africa ===\nIn February 2016, the OCP Group created a new subsidiary named OCP Africa, which is responsible for leading the development of the group on the African fertilizer market through a network of subsidiaries in 5 African countries. The subsidiary was granted the status of Casablanca Finance City (CFC) for investors on the African continent to benefit from an attractive package of tax incentives and other opportunities.<ref name=Agefi>{{cite journal |title=Trading \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve pour le g\u00e9ant marocain des phosphates|url=http://www.agefi.com/quotidien-agefi/suisse/detail/edition/2016-06-03/article/ocp-loffice-cherifien-des-phosphates-vient-douvrir-une-entite-de-negoce-en-suisse-sous-le-nom-de-saftco--428186.html|journal=Agefi|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=OCP Group launches new subsidiary|url=http://www.africanfarming.net/crops/agriculture/ocp-group-launches-new-subsidiary|journal=African Farming|date = March 30, 2016}}</ref> The OCP projects in Africa cover the entire value chain, including the local construction of fertilizer plants, the development of logistics and distribution capabilities, as well as investment in research for the development of formulas adapted for the soils and crops (mapping the African soil fertility and respective fertilizer needs). The African Development Bank (ADB) has pledged to support the various initiatives of the OCP Group in favour of the African continent.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : Akinwumi Adesina chez Terrab, PDG OCP Group|url=http://www.lesafriques.com/actualite/maroc-akinwumi-adesina-chez-terrab-pdg-ocp-group.html?Itemid=89|journal=Les Afriques|date = July 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Le groupe OCP lance sa filiale OCP Africa pour renforcer le d\u00e9veloppement agricole de l'Afrique |url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/02/25/ocp-africa-nouvelle-filiale-developpement-agricole_n_9318388.html |journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire/International/ Le PDG du Groupe OCP re\u00e7oit le Pr\u00e9sident du Groupe de la BAD (Communiqu\u00e9)|url=http://news.abidjan.net/h/595029.html|journal=Abidjan.net|date = July 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=A la COP 22, l'accord sur l'agriculture en friche|url=http://www.liberation.fr/planete/2016/11/17/a-la-cop-22-l-accord-sur-l-agriculture-en-friche_1529165|journal=Lib\u00e9ration|date = November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe OCP Group plans to open 14 new branches in Sub-Saharan Africa to make a promising entry into the African market. The main countries targeted by this operation are: [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Senegal]], [[the Democratic Republic of Congo]], [[Benin]], [[Cameroon]], Nigeria, [[Tanzania]], [[Angola]], [[Zambia]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]], [[Kenya]], [[Ghana]], and [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc : le groupe OCP pr\u00e9voit 14 nouvelles filiales en Afrique subsaharienne|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/08/05/maroc-le-groupe-ocp-prevoit-14-nouvelles-filiales-en-afrique-subsaharienne/|journal=Financial Afrik|date = August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Nigeria]] ====\nIn 2016, the Morrocan head of state and King Mohammed VI presided over the ceremony marking the launch of a strategic partnership for the development of the fertilizer industry in Nigeria. In particular, this partnership includes an agreement between the OCP Group and Dangote Industries Limited for creating a platform for fertilizer production in Nigeria. Similarly, an agreement for developing the fertilizer market was signed between the OCP Group and the association of fertilizer producers and suppliers in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Maroc/Nig\u00e9ria : Plusieurs accords sign\u00e9s aujourd'hui, les d\u00e9tails|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/marocnigeria-plusieurs-accords-signes-aujourdhui-les-details|journal=Infom\u00e9diaire|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi et le Chef de l'Etat nig\u00e9rian pr\u00e9sident la c\u00e9r\u00e9monie de lancement d'un partenariat strat\u00e9gique pour le d\u00e9veloppement de l'industrie des engrais au Nig\u00e9ria|url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-et-le-chef-de-letat-nigerian-president-la-ceremonie-de-lancement-dun-partenariat-strategique-pour-le-developpement-de-lindustrie-des-engrais-au-nigeria/|journal=MA Express|date = December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Accord OCP-Dangote: quand le premier producteur mondial d\u2019engrais tend la main \u00e0 l\u2019homme le plus riche d\u2019Afrique|url=http://www.financialafrik.com/2016/12/03/accord-ocp-dangote-quand-le-premier-producteur-mondial-dengrais-tend-la-main-a-lhomme-le-plus-riche-dafrique/#.WIHjALbhDUI|journal=Financial Afrik|date = December 3, 2016}}</ref> Likewise, a pipeline project linking Nigeria to Morocco, passing through several countries in West Africa, is about to take shape.<ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest |url=http://www.mapexpress.ma/actualite/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-a-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc-reliant-le-nigeria-au-maroc-a-travers-plusieurs-pays-dafrique-de-louest-cabinet-royal/|journal=Agence de presse marocaine|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=SM le Roi pr\u00e9side \u00e0 Casablanca une s\u00e9ance de travail consacr\u00e9e au projet de gazoduc, reliant le Nig\u00e9ria au Maroc \u00e0 travers plusieurs pays d'Afrique de l'ouest|url=http://www.maroc.ma/fr/activites-royales/sm-le-roi-preside-casablanca-une-seance-de-travail-consacree-au-projet-de-gazoduc|journal=Maroc|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Alerte : Le Maroc passe \u00e0 l'acte pour le gazoduc g\u00e9ant, r\u00e9union royale \u00e0 Casablanca|url=http://www.infomediaire.net/news/maroc/alerte-le-maroc-passe-lacte-pour-le-gazoduc-geant-reunion-royale-casablanca|journal=InfoM\u00e9diaire |date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Gazoduc nig\u00e9ria-maroc: le roi pr\u00e9side une s\u00e9ance de travail sur la faisabilit\u00e9 et le financement |url=http://www.bladi.info/threads/gazoduc-nigeria-maroc-roi-preside.445289/|journal=Bladi|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Mohammed VI \u00e9tudie la faisabilit\u00e9 technique et le financement du projet de gazoduc|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/12/13/mohammed-vi-etudie-faisabilite-technique-financement-projet-gazoduc_n_13606152.html?ir=Maroc|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== [[Rwanda]] ====\nIn October 2016, during the visit of King Mohammed VI, the Ministry of Agriculture and Animal Resources signed an agreement with the OCP Group for the construction of a fertilizer plant in the country to facilitate access to these local farmers.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Rwanda's move towards green agric gains momentum|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2016-12-11/206163/|journal=The New Times|date = December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Saftco ===\nOn May 25, 2016, the OCP Group opened a commodity trading entity in Switzerland that includes phosphate, fertilizers and chemical products.<ref name=Agefi/><ref>{{cite journal |title=L'Office ch\u00e9rifien des phosphates ouvre une filiale \u00e0 Gen\u00e8ve|url=http://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/06/03/ocp-geneve-maroc_n_10274720.html|journal=Huffington Post Maghreb|date = June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Financial information ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n |+ Figures 2009 \u2013 2018\n |-\n |\n !scope=\"col\"| 2009\n !scope=\"col\"| 2010\n !scope=\"col\"| 2011\n !scope=\"col\"| 2012\n !scope=\"col\"| 2013\n !scope=\"col\"| 2014\n !scope=\"col\"| 2015\n !scope=\"col\"| 2016\n !scope=\"col\"| 2017\n !scope=\"col\"| 2018 \n |-\n !scope=\"row\"| Turnover (billions of MAD)\n | 25.3\n | 43.5\n | 56.4\n | 59.4\n |46.2\n |41.4\n |47.7\n |42.5\n |48.5\n |55.9\n|-\n ! scope=\"row\" | Profit (billions of MAD)\n | 1.3\n | 8.8\n | 16.3\n | 14.1\n |7.1\n |7.6\n |\n |\n |\n |5.4\n |\n |}\n\n== Executives (2016) ==\n\n=== Top Management ===\n* Chairman & CEO: [[Mostafa Terrab]]\n\n=== Senior Management ===\n* Executive vice president strategy & corporate development : Marouane Ameziane\n* Executive vice president sales & marketing : Mohamed Belhoussain\n* Executive vice president legal & corporate affairs : Otmane Bennani-Smires\n* Executive vice president human capital: Faris Derrij\n* Executive vice president industrial development: Abdelaziz El Mallah\n* Executive vice president industrial operations: Iliass Elfali\n* Executive vice president performance Management : Nada Elmajdoub\n* Executive vice president chief financial officer: Ghislane Guedira\n* Executive vice president digital office : Mohamed Laklalech\n* Executive vice president Africa : Karim Lotfi Senhadji\n\n== 2020 coronavirus crisis response ==\nOCP Group contributed $310 million the Moroccan emergency fund, created by [[Mohammed VI of Morocco|King Mohammed IV]] on 15 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/03/296549/moroccan-government-members-donate-salaries-to-covid-19-fund/|title=Moroccan Government Members Donate Salaries to COVID-19 Fund|last=Hekking|first=Morgan|date=2020-03-17|website=Morocco World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-morocco-idUSKBN212173|title=Morocco to create $1 billion fund to counter coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.ocpgroup.ma/en Official website of the OCP Group]\n* [http://www.ocpafrica.com/ Official website of OCP Africa]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economy of Morocco]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Office Cherifien des Phosphates}}\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Phosphate mining]]\n[[Category:Fertilizer companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Morocco]]\n[[Category:Mining companies of Morocco]]\n", "name_user"